are really different languages, as different as french and italian, although referring to chinese dialects as separate languages is a touchy political issue. like standard mandarin, the "dialects" are all tonal languages. even within mandarin (the large brown language area on the map), pronunciation varies widely between regions and there is often a liberal dose of local slang or terminology to liven up the mix. after mandarin, the largest groups are wu, spoken in the region around shanghai, zhejiang and southern jiangsu, followed by cantonese, spoken in most of guangdong province, hong kong and macau, and the min (fujian) group 